__data__.text: The boundary between the African Plate and the Arabian Plate is represented by the Dead Sea Transform (DST), which is a major zone of left-lateral strike-slip fault.
The DST accommodates the relative northward movement of Arabia with respect to Africa.
The northern end of the DST truncates at the East Anatolian Fault (EAF), which is another major left-lateral strike-slip fault zone.
The EAF accommodates the overall westward movement of the Anatolian Plate as it is extruded in that direction by the northward movement of the Arabian Plate.
The DST and EAF meet at the Marash Triple Junction.
The EAF continues west of the triple junction, forming the boundary between the African and Anatolian plates.
The EAF links into the Cyprus arc to the west via the Latakia Ridge.
The EAF is a 700 km-long (430 mi) fault system, subdivided into seven segments.
The seven segments of the EAF, from the northeast, are the Karlıova, Ilıca, Palu, Pütürge, Erkenek, Pazarcık and Amanos segments.
Some geologists consider the Amanos segment as part of the DST, while others consider it as a transitional structure between the EAF and DST.
A northern strand to the EAF has been recognized, including the Sürgü, Çardak, Savrun, Çokak, Toprakkale, Yumurtalık, Karataş, Yakapınar and Düziçi–İskenderun segments.
The estimated slip rate on the main strand of the EAF system decreases south-westwards from 10 mm (0.39 in) per year on the Karlıova segment down to 2.9 mm (0.11 in) per year on the Amanos segment.
The slip rate on the northern strand is 2.5 mm (0.098 in) per year on the Çardak segment.

The Pazarcık segment in the west has a recurrence interval of 237-772 years for M 7.0-7.4 earthquakes.
The Amanos segment in the west has a recurrence interval of 414-917 years for M 7.0-7.4 earthquakes.
A research paper was published by Earth and Planetary Science Letters in 2002.
The research paper studied stress accumulation and increased seismic hazard along the East Anatolian Fault.
The research paper concluded that two sections of the fault have a considerably high potential for future earthquakes.
One of these sections is located in Elazığ and Bingöl.
The Elazığ and Bingöl section is located between the rupture zones of the 1874 and 1971 earthquakes.
The seismic gap in the Elazığ and Bingöl section ruptured during a Mw  6.1 earthquake in 2010.
The 2020 Mw  6.8 earthquake ruptured to the southwest between the 1893/1905 and 1874 earthquakes.
Another seismic gap is located in Kahramanmaraş.
This Kahramanmaraş gap is a 103 km (64 mi) long section.
The Kahramanmaraş gap is believed to have last ruptured in 1513.
The Kahramanmaraş gap has the potential to produce magnitude 7.3 earthquakes.
Large earthquakes on the northern part of the DST include events in 115, 526, 587, 1138, 1170, and 1822.
These earthquakes resulted in several tens of thousands to several hundreds of thousands of fatalities.
An earthquake sequence occurred.

The United States Geological Survey (USGS) recorded 25 aftershocks with a magnitude Mw 4.0 or greater within six hours of the main tremor.

Thousands of aftershocks were associated with this earthquake.
These aftershocks were distributed along an east-west trend corresponding to the Çardak Fault for about 170 km (110 mi).
A source model for the Mww 7.8 earthquake was produced by the USGS.

This model used three fault segments with individual lengths, widths, strikes and dips of >40 km (25 mi) × 30 km (19 mi), 028°/85° (Segment 1), >175 km (109 mi) × 30 km (19 mi), 060°/85° (Segment 2) and >160 km (99 mi) × 20 km (12 mi), 025°/75° (Segment 3).
The mainshock produced a maximum slip of 11.2 m (37 ft) along Segment 2.

The Mw 7.8 earthquake that occurred on February 6 had a slip extension of 18 km (11 mi) along its rupture area.

A Mw 6.4 aftershock struck Antakya on February 20, with a rupture area of 25 km (16 mi) x 25 km (16 mi) and a peak slip of 0.93 m (3 ft 1 in) at a depth of 8.3 km (5.2 mi).
Preliminary analysis based on the USGS fault model indicates that up to 3 bars of added stress were present near the epicenter of the M7.7 shock on the Çardak–Sürgü Fault.
The Hatay Fault, the source of the 20 February Mw 6.4 aftershock, experienced an increase in stress by 1 bar following the earthquakes on February 6.
The initial rupture of the M7.8 earthquake occurred on the Narlı Fault, the northernmost section of the Dead Sea Transform.
The Narlı Fault ruptured unilaterally to the north until it reached the Pazarcık segment of the East Anatolian Fault.
Ruptures then continued bilaterally to the northeast and southwest along the Pazarcık segment of the East Anatolian Fault.
The initial rupture on the Narlı Fault corresponded to a Mw 7.0 earthquake that lasted for 20 seconds.
The initial rupture on the Narlı Fault had a focal mechanism corresponding to oblique-normal faulting.

A preliminary analysis of near-field seismic records indicates that the initial rupture speed transitioned to supershear after propagating about 19.5 km (12.1 mi) away from the epicenter along the Narlı Fault.

An aftershock with a magnitude of Mw 6.4 occurred on 20 February along the Hatay Fault.

Surface ruptures associated with the M7.8 and M7.7 earthquakes have been mapped using satellite imagery and ground observations.
Pixel matching on images captured by Sentinel-1 before and after the earthquakes revealed two separate zones of surface rupture.

The second earthquake produced 150 km (93 mi) of surface rupture.
Remote sensing using satellite imagery indicated 30 km (19 mi) of surface rupture with a large normal faulting component.
The zone of surface rupture extended from north of Antakya, Hatay Province towards Pazarcık, Kahramanmaraş Province and Gölbaşı, Adıyaman Province.

Liquefaction was identified via satellite and remote sensing along the southern portion of the Mw 7.8 rupture on the East Anatolian Fault from Antakya to Golbasi.
